        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-05-24T01:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-05-24T01:00:00-05:00" n="401" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d401">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/5–2449: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-05-24T14:00:00+08:00">May 24, 1949—2 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 24—7:39 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1100. This is not first time Acting President has asked for statement of support
                    (see Cantel 396, May 17, to Department, repeated Nanking 293, Shanghai 247).
                    With all my sympathy for Li Tsung-jen and his determination to resist
                    Communists, I cannot envisage any <pb facs="0352" n="342" xml:id="pg_342"/>
                    statement US Government could make this late date which would be effective in
                    changing course of military events, which could avoid embroiling us further in
                    Chinese political confusion.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 1100, repeated AmEmb Canton 458, Shanghai 622.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
